If this ode is read with C. ii. 15, and the others mentioned in the Introduction to that ode, the feeling with which Horace entered into the mission of Augustus as the reformor will be better understood.

ARGUMEN T.

Portenta enough hath Jove sent upon the earth, making it afraid lest a new deluge were coming, as the Tiber rolled back from its mouth threatening destruction to the city, the unauthorized avenger of Ilia!

Our sous shall hear that citizens have whetted for each other the steel that should have smitten the enemy.

What god shall we invoke to help us? What prayers shall move Vesta to pity? To whom shall Jove assign the task of wiping out our guilt? Come thou, Apollo ; or thou, smiling Venus, with mirth and love thy companions3 or thou, Mars, our founder, who hast too long sported with war ς or do thou, son of Maia, put on the form of a man and let us call thee the avenger of Caesam nor let our sins drive thee too soon away; here take thy triumphs; be thou our father and our prince, and suffer not the Mede to go unpunished whilst thou art our chief, O Caesar.
